In modern C++ these loops could alternatively be written as:<p><pre><code>  std::vector<int> myVec;
  for( auto it = myVec.begin(); it != myVec.end(); ++it );
</code></pre>
or if you prefer the external begin/end syntax:<p><pre><code>  for( auto it = std::begin(myVec); it != std::end(myVec); ++it );
</code></pre>
or the most succinct (replace && by & if writing):<p><pre><code>  for( auto && item : myVec );</code></pre>

